We can also write
\begin{align*}
[ABC] &= [ACD] + [BCD] \\
&= \frac{1}{2} AC \cdot CD \sin \frac{C}{2} + \frac{1}{2} BC \cdot CD \sin \frac{C}{2} \\
&= 3AC \sin \frac{C}{2} + 3BC \sin \frac{C}{2} \\
&= 3 (AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2}.
\end{align*}Thus,
\[\frac{1}{2} AC \cdot BC \cdot \sin C = 3(AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2}.\]Then
\[AC \cdot BC \sin \frac{C}{2} \cos \frac{C}{2} = 3(AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2},\]so
\[\frac{AC \cdot BC}{3} = 3 (AC + BC).\]Hence,
\[\frac{1}{AC} + \frac{1}{BC} = \frac{AC + BC}{AC \cdot BC} = \boxed{\frac{1}{9}}.\]

Note that $AD = 6,$ $BD = 4,$ and $CD = 2.$  Then by Pythagoras, $AB = 2 \sqrt{13},$ $AC = 2 \sqrt{10},$ and $BC = 2 \sqrt{5}.$  By Heron's Theorem,
\begin{align*}
[ABC]^2 &= (\sqrt{5} + \sqrt{10} + \sqrt{13})(-\sqrt{5} + \sqrt{10} + \sqrt{13})(\sqrt{5} - \sqrt{10} + \sqrt{13})(\sqrt{5} + \sqrt{10} - \sqrt{13}) \\
&= ((\sqrt{10} + \sqrt{13})^2 - (\sqrt{5})^2)((\sqrt{5})^2 - (\sqrt{10} - \sqrt{13})^2) \\
&= (18 + 2 \sqrt{130})(2 \sqrt{130} - 18) \\
&= 196,
\end{align*}so $[ABC] = 14.$

